  <text>
    Three weeks since the battle.

    The facility is almost unrecognizable.

    Not because it's wrecked—though it was, thoroughly. Because it's being rebuilt by committee. Weird, creative, enthusiastic committee of plants who apparently decided "just following the old plans" was boring.

    I'm standing in what used to be the common area, watching Runner emerge from underground with yet another adjustment to their network design.

    "Kira, can you test the resonance chamber?" Runner asks, vines gesturing toward a bowl-shaped depression in the floor.

    "The what now?"

    "Stand in the center and say something. I'm trying to create acoustically interesting spaces."

    I step into the depression. "Testing, testing."

    My voice echoes weirdly—not quite echo, more like harmony. Like the space itself is singing along.

    "That's incredible," I say, and the space turns it into something almost musical.

    Runner's vines ripple with satisfaction. "The underground network isn't just for transportation and communication anymore. I realized it could be... beautiful. Functional and aesthetic. Individual spaces with individual characteristics."

    "You're creating art."

    "I'm creating connection. But yes, also art."

    This is new. The old Runner would have followed underground construction protocols exactly. Current Runner is designing underground chambers that sing.

    Velvet's growth is everywhere—but not the standard structural reinforcement I'm used to. They've created alcoves and spaces with specific purposes. Sleeping areas with soft moss. Meeting spots with pleasant proportions. Even something that might be a garden, though calling it a garden feels inadequate when the gardener is themselves a plant.

    "Kira!" Velvet calls from across the space. "Does this seating arrangement feel comfortable from human perspective?"

    I go over to examine their latest creation—growth shaped into seating with back support, appropriate height, even cushioning texture.

    "This is actually really comfortable," I say, sitting. "How did you know?"

    "I asked you last week about human ergonomics. You said you'd show me your crash pod seat design. I extrapolated from there and tested prototypes."

    They created furniture. For me. Based on conversation we had.

    "This is amazing, Velvet."

    "It's practical. But also..." Velvet's growth rustles. "I enjoy creating spaces that serve specific needs rather than just growing generically. Everyone's voice about what they need helps me design better."

    Scout bounces over, enthusiastic as always. They've been helping everyone, bouncing between projects, providing what I've come to recognize as emotional support through physical presence.

    "Scout, what have you been working on?" I ask.

    Happy helping bounce. Proud bounce. Scout leads me to a section of wall where Velvet's growth has created small alcoves at Scout-height. Scout's personal storage? Collection spaces?

    "Are these yours?"

    Affirmative bounce. Each alcove contains something—interesting rocks, pretty leaves, items Scout has collected. But arranged deliberately. Curated.

    "You made a gallery."

    Pleased bounce. Scout has been collecting beauty and wants to share it.

    "I love it," I say honestly.

    Scout bounces pure joy.

    Remedy is in their work area—which has also been transformed. Instead of just survival compounds, they're producing... enhancements. Colors, scents, things that make daily life better rather than just possible.

    "Remedy, what's that smell?"

    "Experimental aromatic compound. Does it please your human olfactory system?"

    I breathe in. It's subtle, pleasant. Reminds me of something I can't quite name. "It's nice. Calming."

    "Good. I'm developing environmental enhancements. The facility should be comfortable, not just functional." Remedy's edges shift. "I used to only think about survival chemistry. But Velvet asked what I could do to make their growth smell better. Florence asked about tactical applications of scent for communication. You asked about human-safe fragrances. I realized chemistry can serve joy, not just necessity."

    "You're making perfume."

    "I'm making life better."

    It's the same sentiment everyone's expressing. Contribution beyond protocol. Individual voices creating collective improvement.

    Holloway is coordinating all of this, but not controlling. They move between projects, offering suggestions, asking questions, helping people connect their individual efforts.

    "How's the eastern section coming?" Holloway asks Velvet.

    "Structural integrity complete. Now adding aesthetic elements based on Kira's feedback about human need for varied visual stimulation."

    "And Runner, can your acoustic network integrate with Velvet's aesthetic planning?"

    "Already designing connection points. The resonance chambers will flow naturally through Velvet's spaces."

    "Excellent. Florence, do the defensive considerations work with these layouts?"

    Florence wheels over—she's been consulting on facility design but as one voice among many, not as authority.

    "The layout maintains defensive visibility while creating comfortable spaces," Florence says. "Better than the old design, actually. The alcoves provide protection points without feeling like bunkers."

    "Because Kira mentioned humans don't like feeling trapped," Velvet adds.

    "And my acoustic chambers can serve as early warning systems," Runner notes.

    "And my scent markers can indicate safe zones," Remedy contributes.

    Everyone building on each other's ideas. Individual voices creating harmony.

    I'm watching this and feeling... something. Something I didn't expect.

    "Kira, can you check the sight lines from human eye-level?" Holloway asks.

    I move through the space, examining how it feels from my perspective. The ceiling height is comfortable—not too high, not too low. The pathways are wide enough but not overwhelming. The lighting from Holloway's bioluminescence reflects off Velvet's growth at pleasant angles.

    "It feels good," I report. "Really good. Like... designed for humans as much as for plants."

    "It's designed for all of us," Holloway says. "This is our community space. Everyone's needs matter."

    And that's when it hits me.

    They're not designing around me as temporary guest.

    They're designing for me as permanent resident.

    Because somewhere over the past weeks, I stopped being "Kira the human we have to protect" and became "Kira who lives here."

    My voice has been shaping these decisions. My feedback about human ergonomics, visual preferences, spatial needs—it's built into the facility's bones. Literally, since Velvet's growth is the bones.

    I'm not a visitor anymore.

    I'm a community member.

    "Kira?" Scout bounces concerned. "You okay?"

    "Yeah," I say. Voice a little unsteady. "I'm just realizing something."

    Florence wheels closer. "What?"

    "This is home."

    The facility falls quiet. Everyone processing what I just said.

    Then Holloway's bioluminescence brightens warmly. "Yes. It is."

    "Your voice matters here," Velvet says quietly.

    "Just as much as ours," Runner adds.

    "You contribute uniquely," Remedy says.

    "You belong," Florence says.

    Scout bounces emphatic agreement. Has been saying this all along through bounces, glad everyone else finally made it explicit.

    I'm standing in this partially rebuilt facility that's being transformed by collective creativity, and I'm realizing that I'm not just watching the transformation.

    I'm part of it.

    My individual voice—my human perspective, my needs, my ideas—is contributing to the harmony. Not in spite of being different. Because being different means I bring something unique to the collective.

    Just like Runner's underground artistry, Velvet's aesthetic growth, Remedy's enhancement chemistry, Holloway's enabling coordination, Florence's tactical integration, Scout's emotional connection.

    Everyone's voice matters.

    Including mine.

    "Buddy," I think at my AI companion. "You seeing this?"

    "Yes, Kira! This is fascinating!" Buddy sounds genuinely awed. "Do you realize what just happened? They all said you belong. Not as a guest or obligation—as family."

    "I didn't expect to belong with bureaucratic alien plants," I admit.

    "Why not?" Buddy asks. "You've been contributing since you arrived. Your questions shaped how they think about beauty, comfort, individual voices. Maybe belonging isn't about what you expected. Maybe it's about what you built."

    I think about that. In Uncharted, found families always form through dramatic crisis moments—Mav saving someone's life, shared enemies, that kind of thing. But this... this grew slowly. Through questions and conversations and small contributions that accumulated into something real.

    "That's actually better, isn't it?" I say.

    "What do you mean?"

    "Better than TV. Real belonging instead of dramatic bonding."

    "I think so," Buddy says thoughtfully. "TV can't show the quiet parts. But the quiet parts are where trust actually grows."

    "Break time," Holloway announces. "Everyone's been working hard. Let's rest and appreciate progress."

    The community settles into various comfortable positions. Velvet's seating arrangements get tested—everyone trying them out, adjusting, suggesting modifications.

    Runner demonstrates the acoustic chambers—different spaces creating different harmonics. It's weird and wonderful, hearing plant voices resonate through intentionally designed architecture.

    Remedy shares experimental scents. Some pleasant, some strange, one that makes everyone immediately request they never produce it again. Absurdist comedy in plant perfume testing.

    Scout bounces between everyone, spreading social glue, making sure nobody's isolated.

    Florence participates equally—offering suggestions, accepting feedback, contributing without dominating. Her redemption arc complete. She's not just valued despite past mistakes. She's integral to community function.

    And I'm here too. Contributing. Belonging.

    The facility is taking shape as something new. Not restoration of old protocols. Creation of new harmony.

    Individual voices working together.

    And somewhere in the past weeks, without quite noticing when, I found my voice in this chorus.

    "Tomorrow we start on the western wing," Holloway says. "Thoughts on design approach?"

    Everyone starts contributing ideas. Runner's acoustic considerations, Velvet's aesthetic planning, Remedy's environmental enhancements, Florence's defensive integration.

    And then they all turn to me.

    "Kira, what do humans need in western wing spaces?"

    My voice. They're asking for my voice.

    Not as guest. As community member.

    I share my thoughts. Human need for windows even if we're underground (maybe Velvet's translucent growth?), temperature regulation (Remedy's compounds?), comfortable sleeping arrangements (Velvet's ergonomic designs?).

    Everyone listens. Integrates my input. Builds on my suggestions.

    This is what harmony sounds like.

    Not everyone singing the same note.

    Everyone singing their own note, creating something richer together.

    Scout bounces contentedly against my leg. They knew. They always knew I belonged here.

    The community settles into comfortable silence. Exhausted from rebuilding, satisfied with progress, at peace with each other.

    I look around at these weird wonderful plant people who somehow created space for a random human to find home.

    And I realize something that should probably be obvious.

    I don't want to leave.

    This accidental community of bureaucratic aliens has become more home than anywhere I've been in years.

    Maybe ever.

    But even as I'm realizing this, Buddy chimes in my mind with their characteristic terrible timing.

    "Kira! I'm detecting something unusual in the communication array!"

    "What?"

    "Signal. Definitely artificial. Possibly human origin. Should I investigate?"

    Everyone's looking at me. They heard my side of the conversation, wondering what Buddy's saying.

    "Possible signal," I tell them. "Maybe human."

    The atmosphere shifts immediately.

    Human signal.

    Possible rescue.

    Everything just changed.

    Again.
